{
  "doc_id": "43905",
  "text": "Historically, career success was through to reflect predominantly objective rewards, such as an increased salary, upward job movement or a number of promotions. Changes to the world-of-work have seen a shift to promoting subjective career success, measured predominantly as job satisfaction [CITATION_1] . While these viewpoints guided research to date, clarity around what constitutes career success is inconclusive, which is evident in literature that does not agree on a single definition and research that assigns multitude of meanings to career success [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
